A stack is a data structure that follows the Last In First Out (LIFO) principle, meaning that the last item added to the stack is the first one to be removed. Here are the key points of how a stack works:

1. A stack is typically implemented as a collection of nodes, where each node contains a data element and a reference to the previous node in the stack.
2. The top node of the stack is the most recently added node, and is the first one to be removed when items are popped from the stack.
3. To add an item to the stack, a new node is created with the data element and added to the top of the stack. This operation is called pushing.
4. To remove an item from the stack, the top node is removed and discarded. This operation is called popping.
5. It is also possible to access the data element at the top of the stack without removing it, by using a special operation called peeking.

A queue, on the other hand, follows the First In First Out (FIFO) principle, meaning that the first item added to the queue is the first one to be removed. Here are the key points of how a queue works:

1. A queue is typically implemented as a collection of nodes, where each node contains a data element and a reference to the next node in the queue.
2. The front node of the queue is the most recently added node, and is the first one to be removed when items are dequeued from the queue.
3. To add an item to the queue, a new node is created with the data element and added to the end of the queue. This operation is called enqueuing.
4. To remove an item from the queue, the front node is removed and discarded. This operation is called dequeuing.
5. It is also possible to access the data element at the front of the queue without removing it, by using a special operation called peeking.

Here is an example of pseudocode for a stack:
```csharp
class Stack {
  Node top;

  void push(int data) {
    Node newNode = new Node(data);
    newNode.setPrevious(top);
    top = newNode;
  }

  int pop() {
    int data = top.getData();
    top = top.getPrevious();
    return data;
  }

  int peek() {
    return top.getData();
  }
}

class Node {
  int data;
  Node previous;

  Node(int data) {
    this.data = data;
  }

  void setPrevious(Node previous) {
    this.previous = previous;
  }

  int getData() {
    return data;
  }

  int getPrevious() {
    return previous;
  }
}
```
